      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Erbium is a silvery-coloured, soft and malleable metal. It belongs to the lanthanide series. Erbium oxidises in air to produce erbium oxide  - E</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">r</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">2</text>
      </subsup>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">O</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">. In the reaction with water it forms erbium hydroxide  - Er(OH</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">)</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238"> - and hydrogen. It also reacts with acids. Erbium was discovered in 1843 by a Swedish chemist, Carl Gustaf Mosander, and obtained in 1934 by Klemm and Bommer. It was named after the Swedish town of Ytterby.</text>
